Most Popular Vehicles

Riley Zamora

2023-09-27

Abstract

The goal of this analysis is to represent which vehicles are most prominent in the data.

Load in data & Libraries

Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(kableExtra)
library(lubridate)

Data

data <- read.csv("20230921 appraisal activity.csv")

Data Wrangle

Removing NA’s

data <- na.omit(data)

Which Vars are Required

colnames(data)
##  [1] "create_date"             "vin"                    
##  [3] "odometer"                "dealer_id"              
##  [5] "dealer_name"             "dealer_contact_province"
##  [7] "dealer_contact_postal"   "country"                
##  [9] "source_type"             "ph_year"                
## [11] "ph_manuf"                "ph_model"               
## [13] "ph_body"                 "ph_engtype"             
## [15] "trade"                   "market"                 
## [17] "source"

create_date: could be useful if we want to see most popular vehicles by month
vin: not immediately useful might add back later
odometer: could be interesting to see what mileage range shows up most often
dealer_id, dealer_name, etc.: not immediately useful. Performing a different analysis on dealer info
country: most popular by country could be interesting
source_type: not useful
ph_year: year of vehicle is a major component
ph_manuf: which manufacturers are most common
ph_model: model of vehicle is a major component
ph_body: body type of vehicle is a major component
ph_engtype: type of motor is a major component
trade: not useful
market: not useful
source: not useful

Select Vars needed

vehicles <- data |> 
  select(create_date, odometer, country,
         ph_year, ph_manuf, ph_model,
         ph_body, ph_body, ph_engtype)

This data frame vehicles will be called back upon to create smaller, more specific frames.

Check Var Types

sapply(vehicles, class)
## create_date    odometer     country     ph_year    ph_manuf    ph_model 
## "character" "character"   "integer"   "integer" "character" "character" 
##     ph_body  ph_engtype 
## "character" "character"

Factor country. Odometer should be object class numeric. create_date should be object class date. Let’s apply these changes.

Need to account for NULL occurrences in selected columns.

any(vehicles$odometer %in% "NULL")
## [1] TRUE
sum(vehicles$odometer == "NULL")
## [1] 114

I have concluded that there are only NULL vales in odometer column. We will now replace these with 0 before converting to int.

vehicles <- vehicles |> 
  mutate(odometer = ifelse(odometer == "NULL", "0", odometer),
         odometer = as.numeric(odometer),
         country = as.factor(country),
         create_date = as.Date(create_date)
         )
sapply(vehicles, class)
## create_date    odometer     country     ph_year    ph_manuf    ph_model 
##      "Date"   "numeric"    "factor"   "integer" "character" "character" 
##     ph_body  ph_engtype 
## "character" "character"

Odometer

To look at the odometer popularity, we will need to cohort them into increments of 15,000 miles. Then we will be able to view what ranges of miles are being searched for the most often. However, there are some discrepancies within the data that need attention. First of all, some vehicles has misentered odometer readings.

# create base frame for odometer
odo_frame <- vehicles |> 
  select(odometer)

Now lets see what the max and min values are.

max(odo_frame$odometer)
## [1] 1e+10

Now that’s a lot of miles. Let’s do the same for min miles.

min(odo_frame$odometer)
## [1] -514

Hmmm.

We have already adjusted for NULL entries to be 0 so we will adjust for that as well. I believe there were 114 NULL occurrences.

odo_frame |> 
  filter(odometer == 0) |> 
  nrow()
## [1] 1108

There are 1108 values for 0. Since this is a reasonable size, keep in mind 114 of them are NULL and the others may be unknown before.

Let’s see how many vehicles have more than say 500,000 miles.

odo_frame |> 
  filter(odometer > 500000) |> 
  nrow()
## [1] 818

For these 818, we will simply remove them. We will also create our cohorts of 15,000 miles

# remove unwanted inputs
odo_frame <- odo_frame |> 
  filter(odometer >= 0 & odometer < 500000) |> 
  mutate(cohort = (odometer %/% 15000) * 15000) |> 
  mutate(CohortLabel = case_when(
    cohort == 0 ~ "0 to 15,000",
    cohort > 0 ~ paste0(cohort + 1, " to ", cohort + 15000)
  ))

Now that we have created our cohorts, we can add in our grouping and counts to see which odometer ranges are the most used.

odo_grouped <- odo_frame |> 
  group_by(CohortLabel) |> 
  summarise(count = n()) |> 
  arrange(desc(count))

kable(head(odo_grouped), format = 'html') |> 
  column_spec(2, width = "1.5cm")
CohortLabel count
15001 to 30000 315993
30001 to 45000 298594
0 to 15,000 298225
45001 to 60000 229932
60001 to 75000 205338
75001 to 90000 176824

As you can expect the higher the miles the less searches they show up in. There is some variation to this in the first few rows. I chose not to make a visual because it would be pretty boring to look at.

Putting it together

Let’s combine manufacturer, model, body, and engine type to see what specific vehicles are actually being sought out the most.

combined_frame <- vehicles |> 
  select(ph_manuf, ph_model, ph_body, ph_engtype, ph_year) |> 
  group_by(ph_manuf, ph_model, ph_body, ph_engtype, ph_year) |>
  summarise(count = n()) |>

Looking at Some Other Aspects

In this section we will do some deeper analysis into the vehicles by country. We will also take a look into the time frames that dealers are looking for different cars. This could be useful to see if there is any seasonality in the data.

Sep_top_vehicles <- month_frame |> 
  filter(month == 'Sep') |> 
  group_by(ph_manuf, ph_model, ph_body, ph_engtype, ph_year) |>
  summarise(count = n()) |> 
  arrange(desc(count))
